<TEXT>
<P>
 More than 500 inmates battled each other for several hours in four separate 
brawls at the Peter J. Pitchess Honor Rancho near Castaic late Wednesday and 
early Thursday, but the fighting caused no serious injuries, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 The violence, which broke out between Latino and African American prisoners at 
the jail, is the latest in a series of brawls between the two groups. 
</P>
<P>
 A sheriff's spokesman said it was unclear what led to the disturbances, but in 
the past authorities have blamed the fights on a power struggle between African 
American and Latino inmates. 
</P>
<P>
 Early Thursday, when inmates battled with broomsticks and razors and were 
stopped by sheriff's deputies spraying rubber bullets, 17 prisoners suffered 
minor cuts and bruises, spokesman Gabe Ramirez said. 
