<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONSORTIUM TO PUT $1.8 BILLION IN PHONE SYSTEM; TELECOMMUNICATIONS: 
PARTNERSHIP, TO BE KNOWN AS GLOBALSTAR, WILL INVEST IN SATELLITE-BASED NETWORK. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A worldwide consortium of 10 telecommunications companies, including PacTel 
Corp., announced plans Thursday to invest in a $1.8-billion satellite-based 
telephone network aimed at undercutting competitors' costs by simplifying the 
connections between Earth and space. 
</P>
<P>
 Led by Loral Corp. and Qualcomm Inc., the partnership, called Globalstar, will 
offer cheap rates by taking advantage of existing networks operated by local 
phone companies, such as the regional Bell operating companies and their 
foreign counterparts.It is expected to begin operating in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
 Among the new partners is PacTel, the Walnut Creek, Calif., wireless 
communication company that on April 1 will be spun free of Pacific Telesis 
Group, also the parent company of Pacific Bell. PacTel will invest $37.5 
million for an 8.3% stake. 
</P>
<P>
 Forging worldwide telecommunications links, either by satellite or by 
fiber-optic technology, has grown into an intense focus of competition, as 
governments and private companies seek to develop information networks. 
</P>
<P>
 By using existing local ground networks to beam calls to an international 
satellite network, the Globalstar system will be able to use fewer and less 
complex satellites than other mobile communications systems, its developers 
say. 
</P>
<P>
 Loral and Qualcomm's partners are the United Kingdom's Vodafone, France's 
Alcatel Espace, Italy's Alenia Spazio, PacTel and Space Systems/Loral of the 
United States, the South Korean companies Hyundai and Dacom, and Deutsche 
Aerospace in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
 For PacTel, soon to be AirTouch Communications, this agreement marks the first 
major foray into long-distance service. 
</P>
<P>
 Once it is independent of the local California phone company, it will be freed 
of restrictions on offering long-distance service. PacTel will have exclusive 
rights to provide mobile service in the United States, Japan, six other 
countries and the Caribbean region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
