<P>
2 SOMALI WARLORDS AGREE TO CEASE-FIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A day after the United Nations announced that it was giving up on peace talks 
for Somalia, the country's two most powerful warlords agreed Thursday to 
arrange a cease-fire and set up a new government. 
</P>
<P>
 But the agreement between Gen. Mohammed Farah Aidid and Ali Mahdi Mohamed does 
not ensure stability.Previous agreements have quickly fallen apart. 
</P>
<P>
 The latest came only after the United Nations, exasperated by the failure of 
two weeks of talks in the Kenyan capital, said it would stop paying food and 
hotel costs for the negotiators from Somalia's 15 rival factions. 
</P>
<P>
 In Washington, President Clinton praised the accord: "Because of their 
courageous efforts, Somalia can now build its own future, a step it made in the 
right direction today with the accord between the leaders of the two largest 
factions in that country." 
