<HEADLINE>
<P>
VISITATION RIGHTS; COUNTY SUES TO END HOMEOWNERS' PARKING BAN ON PRIVATE 
ROADWAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL GRANBERRY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The disputed territory is only a few feet away from some of the most expensive 
real estate in Southern California. The homes along Isle Vista here are valued 
between $1 million and $3 million. And the views are nothing short of 
spectacular. 
</P>
<P>
 The problem, homeowners say, is that outsiders feel increasingly entitled to 
share the breathtaking sunsets and glimpses of Santa Catalina Island by parking 
on their exclusive street and walking to a popular park to take in the majestic 
scenery. 
</P>
<P>
 Isle Vista is a private road, as are the Gatsby-like estates of the 161-member 
Monarch Point Homeowners Assn. that claim it as an address. But Badlands Park 
-- one of the highest, most scenic points in all of Orange County -- is public. 
</P>
<P>
 Deciding to end their frustration, the homeowners in 1992 took the liberty of 
declaring their street off limits. They put up no-parking signs and painted the 
curbs red to emphasize that most of Isle Vista -- the only access to the park 
-- is private. 
</P>
<P>
 This is where lawyers enter the picture. As county government sees it, 
painting curbs and erecting signs went too far. 
</P>
<P>
 So, Orange County officials filed suit earlier this month, seeking a permanent 
injunction against the association, as well as a $30,000 fine and payment of 
all legal costs. The homeowners' paint job and signs violate the California 
Coastal Act, the suit alleges, and could result in fines of $10,000 a day for 
each day they violate the act -- should a judge agree with the county. 
</P>
<P>
 The act seeks to protect access to publicly owned coastal areas like Badlands 
Park. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's unfortunate that we had to press the point to litigation," said John 
Sibley, deputy director of the Orange County Environmental Management Agency, 
which made repeated demands to the homeowners to remove the self-imposed 
no-parking area. 
</P>
<P>
 The association's attorney, William P. Hickey, counters that his clients 
obtained no permission to paint the curb from any governmental agency for the 
simple reason that "they just don't need it." 
</P>
<P>
 "We hope the county acts reasonably, but at this point, it's hard for us to 
tell why they're doing what they're doing," Hickey said. 
</P>
<P>
 The homeowners maintain that plenty of parking space exists along the northern 
end of Isle Vista and that declaring the curbed area near Badlands a no-parking 
zone was based solely on safety -- for park visitors and property owners. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The private street is the only access to the recreational facility, which has 
no parking lots. Residents are worried that public parking near the entrance 
could block emergency vehicles from reaching their homes. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a school bus pickup area," Hickey said. "When cars are parked there, the 
cars of homeowners can't get through. Fire access is also an issue." 
</P>
<P>
 But public access to Badlands can "reasonably be made" only from Isle Vista, 
the suit maintains. The red paint and no-parking signs "effectively denied the 
public access over Isle Vista Drive," the suit says. 
</P>
<P>
 The no-parking signs and red curbs were an issue once before, in 1988, when 
the homes were about to be built. In anticipation, the developer put up signs 
and painted the curbs red. But as a condition of obtaining a coastal 
development permit, the developer agreed to remove the signs and paint, 
according to Edward N. Duran, deputy county counsel. 
</P>
<P>
 But by June, 1992, county officials discovered that the paint and no-parking 
signs had reappeared, Duran said. 
</P>
<P>
 In spite of "repeated demands" by the county ever since, the homeowners' 
association has "refused to remove these obstructions," the suit says. 
</P>
<P>
 A security attendant, who asked not to be identified, said an incident in 
mid-1992 prompted the decision by homeowners to paint the curbs red all the way 
from the guard house, which stands at the entrance to the estates, to a point 
several hundred feet down the street. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The guard described the incident this way: Fire had broken out in a 
homeowner's back yard. But firetrucks stalled at the guard house, because cars 
belonging to park visitors had made the entrance impassable. The homeowner 
doused the fire, and damage was averted, "but it could have been a disaster," 
the guard said. 
</P>
<P>
 Not everyone agrees that parking on Isle Vista is an evil. 
</P>
<P>
 Two residents who asked not to be named said they welcome the park's daily 
visitors who use the Badlands trails to leisurely walk their dogs. They chose 
not to comment further, they said, hoping not to offend fellow homeowners. 
</P>
<P>
 However, Joseph Potocki, a marketing consultant who lives in one of the 
estates, called the park an asset in every way except one. 
</P>
<P>
 "It would be a hazard to anybody coming out of the guarded-gate area if cars 
are allowed to park right there. There just isn't enough space," he said. "I 
find it difficult to believe that the county would favor that from a safety 
standpoint. It's too narrow a space. I don't think it's doable." 
</P>
<P>
 But the suit seeks to eliminate the entire red-zoned area imposed by the 
residents, even near the entrance to the guarded gate, which is barely wide 
enough for a single car. 
</P>
<P>
 "The association is eager to do the right thing," said Hickey, the homeowners' 
attorney. "We don't feel we're denying access to a public park and that we're 
complying with their request under the law and under the Coastal Act. Even now, 
visitors to the park have to walk maybe 50 feet. 
</P>
<P>
 "Why is the county so concerned about walking such a short distance in order 
to get to a hiking trail? Isn't walking the point here, anyway?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
