<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ANAHEIM; HOPING KIDS TAKE SCIENCE TO HEART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It's hoped that a new program making the rounds of county schools will produce 
some future scientists by letting elementary students listen to their own 
heartbeats and those of animals. 
</P>
<P>
 Heart Beats premiered Thursday at Jonas Salk Elementary School, where 30 
fifth-graders took turns using a stethoscope and learned how the heart powers 
the body. 
</P>
<P>
 They listened to their heartbeats, at rest and after exercise, and to the 
heartbeats of a chicken and a snake. 
</P>
<P>
 It's part of the Science Jamboree on Wheels, an education program sponsored by 
the nonprofit Discover Science Center in Costa Mesa. The program aims to 
educate students about their bodies and how to stay healthy. 
</P>
<P>
 More importantly, it hopes to interest elementary students in science, 
according to Bill D'Angelo, the program's spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
 "We want them to grow up to become scientists, and have fun while doing that," 
D'Angelo said. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to tuning it their hearts, students "dissected" a seven-foot doll, 
whose chest unzips to reveal fabric replicas of the lungs, intestines and other 
internal organs. 
</P>
<P>
 Donna Wirfs of Discovery Science Center guided the students during the 
45-minute medical examination of Stuffee, the anatomical doll. The doll was 
brought into the classroom in a wheelchair by technicians in white coats. 
</P>
<P>
 The demonstration for Susan Bock's fifth-grade class will be repeated in other 
schools around the county in the coming months, D'Angelo said. BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</TEXT>
